            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "Obviously it's subjective, but I'd argue that \"stop\" implies that the lsp is not disabled. This lines up with current documentation: for example, see the usage of the term \"stop\" in the [LSP FAQs](https://neovim.io/doc/user/lsp.html#lsp-faq), and [`vim.lsp.enable(..., false)`](https://neovim.io/doc/user/lsp.html#vim.lsp.enable()) is described as disabling, with the added note (in parenthesis) that it `actively stops and detaches clients as needed` as part of this disabling.\n\nAdditionally, calling `:LspStop` on an already stopped client will only disable it, and will not perform any stop action at all. This feels rather unintuitive to me.",
