            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> It's both. `enable()` has overlap with \"stop\". LspStop does actively call `client.stop`:\n> \n> [nvim-lspconfig/plugin/lspconfig.lua](https://github.com/neovim/nvim-lspconfig/blob/a89bfcfd0e44f898341ac8a80ba83ccf6218bef3/plugin/lspconfig.lua#L279)\n> \n> Line 279 in [a89bfcf](/neovim/nvim-lspconfig/commit/a89bfcfd0e44f898341ac8a80ba83ccf6218bef3)\n>  client.stop(force) \n> \n\n`client.stop()` is only used in the legacy implementation. Note that it doesn't do this in the 0.11 version (except for the logic to force stop, which will be removed once auto-escalating stop is upstreamed):\n\nhttps://github.com/neovim/nvim-lspconfig/blob/a89bfcfd0e44f898341ac8a80ba83ccf6218bef3/plugin/lspconfig.lua#L182\n\nAfter all, `:LspStop lua` is equivalent to `:lua vim.lsp.enable('lua', false)`.",
